{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8cfc6617-4f6c-45fb-a8b2-ab4abd7767cb","content":"There's no repo content here to reference, so here's the general guidance:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Check for macOS crash reports** — look in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** before running:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n\n3. **Run the app again** — when it crashes, a core file will be written to the configured path (e.g., `/tmp/core.<pid>`).\n\n4. **Analyze with `lldb`:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, you may need to boot into recovery mode and run `csrutil enable --without debug`, or use `lldb` to attach live:\n   ```bash\n   lldb /path/to/your/app\n   run\n   # after crash, use `bt`, `thread list`, `register read`, etc.\n   ```\n\n**Key note for NativeAOT:** Since there's no managed runtime, you won't get managed stack traces from `createdump`/SOS. Use `lldb` with the app's debug symbols (`.dSYM` bundle) for the best experience.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"91a6589f-9f63-4acf-879b-7cab6bbe9e94","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The working directory appears to be empty and there's no relevant repository content. This is a general knowledge question about macOS crash dump recovery for NativeAOT apps. Let me answer from my knowledge.","outputTokens":398,"requestId":"608C:1230E4:2DDFD0:3BE15B:69FFE484"},"id":"623c19c3-d9fd-4e27-b7a6-1e2d41add662","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:51:10.985Z","parentId":"25ff8f7e-fd28-4860-bfc1-dea3b4b29af4"}
